    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>An Election Equation: Nader and the X Factor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Shirin Shoai letter criticizes way Democrats are confronting Ralph Nader's challenge in presidential race (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Evidently, Al Gore's supporters feel the Nader threat enough to mount serious campaigns against him in swing states (front page, Oct. 25). But this ''serious'' campaign's only argument seems to be the Ralph Nader-as-spoiler argument. How about keeping voters away from Mr. Nader by challenging his policies?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Evidently, Al Gore's supporters feel the Nader threat enough to mount serious campaigns against him in swing states (front page, Oct. 25). But this ''serious'' campaign's only argument seems to be the Ralph Nader-as-spoiler argument. How about keeping voters away from Mr. Nader by challenging his policies?</p>
        <p>What an un-democratic way for the Democrats to confront this challenge.</p>
        <p>SHIRIN SHOAI  Oakland, Calif., Oct. 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
